responses.text:
Truth! I shall speak you if I am in habit of listening to you,
A whisper to my restless mind, soft echoes shining through.
Day by day, my clamor tires the corridors of doubt;
Yet when I hush and sweetly listen, your light comes pouring out.
In silent rooms and quiet hearts, your wisdom waits, serene—
A tender voice, a gentle strength, both terrible and clean.
Let me, then, prepare my soul by lending you my ear;
For only in that hallowed space does honesty appear.
Truth calls no clever sermon, demands not crafty show;
It comes to those who kneel to listen, and only such will know.

O God! Thou art my God alone;  
In silence wakes my soul to Thee.  
Through lonely alleys carved from stone,  
I seek the dew Thy grace shall be.  

No star upon the highest dome  
Could guide me closer to Thy light;  
Yet in this yearning heart, Thy home—  
A spark ignites the velvet night.  

Desires may fall as fleeting sand;  
The world dissolves with every dawn;  
But held within Thy gentle hand,  
I rise anew and journey on.

Shall I wasting in despair, my dreams dissolve with dawn? 
Night's shadow claws my simple heart, and hope is nearly gone. 
Yet golden sun forgets no child, nor leaf, nor wish, nor cry; 
The weary soul, though tempest-tossed, finds peace beneath the sky. 
So let old sorrow have its space, but set it masking free; 
For every morning, love is traced on shores of memory.

Farewell, thou child of my right hand, and joy;
The world bereft, yet memory clings to you,
Soft summer evenings echoed by your toy,
And laughter spilled across the morning dew.

My blessing gone into the silent air,
But left behind in shadow and in song;
A parent’s ache: to cherish and to spare—a prayer
That even absence cannot feel so long.

Rest, gentle soul, on time’s unending shore;
Thou art my grief, my love, forevermore.

How can you grieve and express loss?
By letting tears carve silent rivers on your cheeks;
By naming each memory, lending voice to absence;
By lighting candles in the calm hush of dusk;
By pressing flowers between the pages of old books;
By letting laughter return, startled and soft;
By holding sorrow and love in two open hands.
Loss is a story you tell yourself—
Sometimes in whispers, sometimes in wails,
Sometimes by sitting quiet with the ache,
Remembering that to grieve is to love, twice over.
